an eye to the implications for human rights, multiculturalism, and integration, the contributors to this book draw on qualitative interviews, policy, and media analysis to examine state practices towards, and media representations of, Arab Canadians. They also present voices that counter the dominant discourse and trace forms of community resistance to the racialization of Arab Canadians. Targeted Transnationals concludes with reflections on the challenges to integration, and the relevance of multiculturalism in the context of globalization and transnationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArabsxCivil rightszCanada. 0aArabsxPress coveragezCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Cultural Policy.2bisacsh1 aAbu-Laban, Yasmeen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmery, Zainab, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntonius, Rachad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDakroury, Aliaa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan, Wafaa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHennebry, Jenna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHennebry, Jenna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKowalski, Jeremy D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabelle, Micheline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMomani, Bessma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMomani, Bessma, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRocher, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalha, Dina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Andrew S., 